Then the optimum pH level of the reaction is studied. The N-CDs fluorescence has almost no change in the pH range of 3–10 (Fig. S7), but plunges under strong acidic (pH less than 3) and alkaline (pH > 11). Simultaneously, the absorption spectrum of 4-NP is deeply modulated by the pH of the solution as described in the above experience experiments (Fig. 3(c)). Under alkaline conditions, the dissociation of H+ from hydroxyl results in the bathochromic shift of the 4-NP absorption band from 320 to 400 nm, enhancing the L-IFE relationship between N-CDs and 4-NP. As described in Fig. 4(b), when the pH level is 8, the quenching efficiency reaches a maximum value. Therefore, the pH of the 4-NP solution is set at 8 (Ahmed et al., 2015; Johnson et al., 2013). Whereafter, the incubation time for the sensing system is optimized. As shown in Fig. 4(c), the fluorescence intensity ratio value (I468
                        /I390
                        ) of the system significantly rises at the beginning incubation of 2 min and therewith becomes stable. Consequently, 2 min is determined as the reaction time.
